Undergraduate Statistics Society (USS) R-WORKSHOP 2021¶

Welcome to the R Workshop! Our goal today is to introduce you to Data Science and Statistics in R!

What is Data Science?¶

Data Science combines the fields of Computer Science, Mathematics and Statistics to create insights and make sense of data in a meaningful way. It is a key part of every industry now a days!

Examples of Data Science in the real world:

  • Predicting malignant breast cancer tumours through machine learning
  • Self driving cars
  • Supply chain optimization for companies such as Amazon to shorten delivery time
  • Targetting ads based off user behaviour on websites

What is R?¶

R is a programming language developed by statisticians. It was designed specifically for data analysis and has many useful libraries great for data wrangling, analysis, visualization, and machine learning.

Lets do some exploratory analysis! Question: How can we look at the relationship between math score and reading score?

Scatterplots are used to compare 2 variables, to see if there may be a relationship between them. ggplot2 is a great package for data visualization. Fill in the ... in the following code to create a scatterplot:

In [ ]:
# this is the syntax for ggplot scatterplots

#  ggplot(df, aes(x= ... , y= ...)) +
#         geom_point()
In [17]:
ggplot(df, aes(x= math_score, y=reading_score)) +
        geom_point()

Q: Based on the plot, can you tell if there is a relationship between the two variables, and if so what type?

To visualize a categorical variable and a continous variable we can use side by side bar plots, using geom_col instead of geom_point. Lets look at Parent Education Level and Math score.

    geom_col(color="blue")

Hmm, does this look right? No, we can't interpret this bar graph. We need to calculate the average math score of each parent education level separately. How can we do this?

Solution: Lets use the pipe operator %>%, and the functions group_by and summarize. %>% is used to apply a sequence of functions

In [20]:
# calculate summary statisitcs 

df_math <- df %>% group_by(parent_edu_level) %>%
    summarize(av_math_score = mean(math_score))
In [22]:
# another example calculating median via summarize

df_math_median <- df %>% group_by(parent_edu_level) %>%
    summarize(med_math_score = median(math_score))

df_math_median

Now we can finally make our bar graph! I am also changing the titles of the axis's here. With ggplot you can add layers to change things such as the titles.

In [23]:
ggplot(df_math, aes(x=parent_edu_level, y=av_math_score)) +
    labs(x="Parental Education Level", y="Average Math Score")+
    geom_col( color="blue")

Based on the above template, figure out what goes in the ... to make a scatterplot to show the relationship between reading and writting score, based on whether or not not they took the prep course

ggplot(df, aes(x=reading_score,y=writting_score)) + geom_point() + 
    facet_wrap(~test_prep_course)

What do the scatterplots show us?

We can see that their is a strong positive linear relationship between reading scores and writting scores.

We can also see that the lowest scores were people with no test prep course

Since there is a strong linear relationship here, can we use someones reading score to predict writting score?

Lets fit a linear model! R has a built in function lm()

In [25]:
# simple linear regression model 

reg <- lm(writting_score ~ reading_score, data=df)

Simple linear regression minimizes the sum of squares of prediction error to get the least square regression line

minimize $\Sigma(y_{i} - b_{0} - b_{1}x)^2$

$\hat{y} = b_{0} + b_{1}x_{i}$

$b_{0}$ is the intercept $b_{1}$ is the coefficient learned by the model

we can use the summary(reg) to look at our model

In [26]:
summary(reg)

Call:

How can we tell if our model is good?

  • look at R^2 value

$R^2$ represents the percentage of the variance of the response variable that can be explained by the predictor variables of our model. It is a measure of how good our regression line fits the data.

perfect $R^2$ value is 1

In [27]:
summary(reg)$r.squared
0.911257488891314

Wow! Since this is very close to 1, it means our model is a good fit

What if we want to add in more predictor varibles? Can R handle categorical variables such as test_prep_course ?

For binary variables, R uses one as a baseline, which is why we only see test_prep_coursenone above.

How do we know if a coefficient is important?

  1. does adding it increase adjusted R^2 value?
  2. is it significant?

We know whether a coeefficient is significant by looking at it's p-value in the summary output.

Test: $H_{0}$: coefficient = 0 vs $H_{a}$: coefficient $\neq$ 0

Test statistic: $\frac{B_{i}-\beta_{i}}{se(B_{i})}$ ~ $t_{n-k}$

Thankfully R does this for us! Look at the P(>|t|) in the summary ouput for significance! We see that all the coefficients are significant at alpha=0.001.
